51
00:04:14,781 --> 00:04:21,885
And that all changed for me when my mother-in-law got sick and I had to be the interpreter for our family.

52
00:04:22,005 --> 00:04:27,368
Like I was the one that was explaining to my husband and his family what was going on with his mom.

53
00:04:28,675 --> 00:04:34,360
and ended up having to leave my job to care for my mother.

54
00:04:34,540 --> 00:04:56,739
And with that caretaker role, it really opened my eyes to how desperately our healthcare system is broken and also how we're not taking care, unless you have a support system, an internalized support system, as a society, we're not taking care of people who are elderly, ill, disabled, and that we really needed to do something about it.

55
00:04:57,616 --> 00:05:03,541
And I remember sitting at my mother-in-law's hospital bed when I told her I quit my job.

56
00:05:03,821 --> 00:05:05,302
She was just devastated.

57
00:05:05,322 --> 00:05:06,584
She was like, why would you do that?

58
00:05:06,724 --> 00:05:07,604
You need a job.

59
00:05:08,225 --> 00:05:10,206
And I said, no, we need to take care of you.

60
00:05:10,347 --> 00:05:12,308
And that's the priority right now.

61
00:05:13,489 --> 00:05:21,075
And I said, as God is my witness, I don't know how and I don't know when and I don't know how I'm gonna get there, but I want my job to be eliminated.

62
00:05:21,216 --> 00:05:25,779
I don't think an insurance verification specialist is something that needs to exist in the universe.

63
00:05:27,128 --> 00:05:30,310
And it seems corny, but it's kind of how I got started.

64
00:05:30,490 --> 00:05:47,419
And I took care of her and she only survived maybe about a year after I quit my job, but she passed away and four months later, Trump got elected and it just put a fire under my tail.

65
00:05:47,620 --> 00:05:50,381
And I was like, this is it, this is what I have to do.

66
00:05:50,461 --> 00:05:53,503
I don't know what I'm gonna do, I don't know how I'm gonna do it, but I dove in.

67
00:05:54,083 --> 00:05:55,264
And I became a full-time activist.

68
00:05:57,179 --> 00:05:59,880
And activism came so naturally to me.

69
00:05:59,920 --> 00:06:09,143
And I never realized how much I had been advocating and pushing things along in my natural just way of being.

70
00:06:10,764 --> 00:06:16,646
And I, as an activist, as a full-time activist, I jumped into it 110%.

71
00:06:17,606 --> 00:06:24,468
And with that activism, I was able to not only start to advocate, you know, against the Trump

72
00:06:25,218 --> 00:06:27,559
immigration deportation machine.

73
00:06:27,999 --> 00:06:33,721
I was able to stand up for, you know, the Muslim ban, women's rights, all sorts of things.

74
00:06:33,821 --> 00:06:41,604
And I realized that on the federal level, we had a great group of Congress people, you know, like they were fighting for the same thing.

75
00:06:41,624 --> 00:06:48,966
So it seemed ridiculous to constantly be calling Catherine Clark to save the ADA or save this or save that.

76
00:06:49,946 --> 00:06:54,248
And so I found the State House was a place that I could really evoke change.

77
00:06:55,533 --> 00:07:17,438
And at the State House, I started lobbying for things like the Safe Communities Act, which was a bill that would ensure due process for everyone in this country, which in, again, I'm not a constitutional law person, but in my eyes, it should be expanded to cover anyone who resides in this country, full stop.

78
00:07:18,059 --> 00:07:18,899
Everyone should have their day.

79
00:07:21,778 --> 00:07:36,787
And then, again, just little by little, I started advocating and working, and I was able to become a leader in the Indivisible movement, and I helped found the Indivisible Massachusetts State Group, and I was part of their board.

80
00:07:37,828 --> 00:07:45,593
I also started doing work with MoveOn nationally and was able to work on different presidential elections, things like that.

81
00:07:45,613 --> 00:07:49,555
I was a proud supporter of JuliÃ¡n Castro last 2020.

82
00:07:51,684 --> 00:08:01,061
But that work also helped me realize that it was really happening on the ground, the closer as you, as we mentioned earlier, the closer you get to municipal work.

83
00:08:02,777 --> 00:08:06,660
the more localized it is, the more change you can actually create.

84
00:08:08,181 --> 00:08:15,906
And with that, I got really involved during the pandemic, as you said, with a mutual aid group.

85
00:08:16,086 --> 00:08:28,534
And we, I was one of the founders of a mutual aid group in Malden, which we were able to help hundreds of people, again, navigate a dizzying system, figuring out how to fill out unemployment.

86
00:08:28,594 --> 00:08:31,756
You know, people were immediately unemployed and had no idea, had never been

87
00:08:32,762 --> 00:08:34,883
without a job and didn't know how to file for unemployment.

88
00:08:34,923 --> 00:08:40,664
People didn't know how to file for RAFT or any of the other housing monies that were out there.

89
00:08:40,984 --> 00:08:54,187
And every day we were getting calls from people who were either food insecure, housing insecure, scared of how to manipulate and manage through the government stuff.

90
00:08:54,227 --> 00:08:56,548
And we were able to find support for them.

91
00:08:57,258 --> 00:09:11,513
We created a food pantry out of the Kung Fu Academy here in Malden and, you know, distributed hundreds of meals, not only, you know, the meals on wheel stuff, but we were able to create culturally competent meals for folks.

92
00:09:11,593 --> 00:09:12,274
So we had a

93
00:09:12,795 --> 00:09:22,201
We had a Chinese, we had the Chinese elders day where we would, and it was one of my favorite things to do is to deliver meals to Chinese elders every Friday afternoon.

94
00:09:23,181 --> 00:09:29,305
And, you know, making sure we had masa on hand and other, you know, ethnically competent foods.

95
00:09:30,646 --> 00:09:37,610
And that work really taught me that advocacy, when paired with government work, you can really evoke change.

96
00:09:39,111 --> 00:09:52,380
advocating for housing rights and figuring out how to keep people in their house, I was able to push the mayor here in Malden to create a moratorium on evictions.

97
00:09:52,960 --> 00:09:55,562
And we were the first city in the state to do that.

98
00:09:56,182 --> 00:10:01,586
And with that work, I was able to build upon that and we created the housing stability department here.

99
00:10:02,423 --> 00:10:08,195
And in that in that creation since I believe 2000 I'm sorry 2021 we've been able to keep 2000 people in their homes.

100
00:10:12,733 --> 00:10:16,576
not just in Malden, but in their actual home that they still live in.

101
00:10:17,637 --> 00:10:25,083
And it's an amazing, it's amazingly transformative to see that, you know, you have this idea and then watch it kind of grow.

102
00:10:25,163 --> 00:10:34,891
It's not, I didn't imagine I would create a bureaucracy or a department, but to be able to solve the problem of keeping people in their house was so,

103
00:10:36,833 --> 00:10:45,858
monumental to me that it really proved to me that, you know, one person with enough support and enough gumption can make things make change.

104
00:10:47,419 --> 00:11:00,607
That being said, to run for office, I never thought that I was the front of the store kind of person, but I've really been compelled and asked by so many of my neighbors, like, why aren't you leading?

105
00:11:01,726 --> 00:11:05,709
And honestly, the question is, it turned out to be a really good question.

106
00:11:06,029 --> 00:11:11,133
They say that you have to ask women at least seven times to run for office before they do.

107
00:11:12,334 --> 00:11:20,580
And, you know, I had a lot of family obligations that kind of held me back from really trying to put my all into this.

108
00:11:21,621 --> 00:11:26,205
And those, you know, having long conversations with my family, they are ready, and so I was ready.

109
00:11:27,571 --> 00:11:30,273
Oh, it's a great, great story.

