00:13:09,129 --> 00:13:11,150
I have been a victim of police violence.

129
00:13:11,190 --> 00:13:13,271
So I relate and understand.

130
00:13:13,851 --> 00:13:18,554
And so I think that I bring that type of lens into this work.

131
00:13:19,894 --> 00:13:23,777
And obviously, when the Black Lives Matter movement really got going,

132
00:13:26,172 --> 00:13:28,313
It was, I thought, transformative.

133
00:13:29,134 --> 00:13:32,696
And I wish that that energy was still kind of moving us forward.

134
00:13:32,756 --> 00:13:34,797
I think that it's kind of died down.

135
00:13:36,058 --> 00:13:44,944
But to my work that I've done with the lens of equity inclusion, I was part of a

136
00:13:45,832 --> 00:13:50,834
racial equity group here in Malden that was able to start having conversations.

137
00:13:50,934 --> 00:14:01,980
Because honestly, I think that that's one of the biggest problems that we have, is that we don't have a common language and a common understanding of what bias and prejudice and racism is.

138
00:14:03,160 --> 00:14:05,181
And I think people don't know what they don't know.

139
00:14:05,561 --> 00:14:10,784
And so even just starting with conversations, and some people would be like, no, we need action.

140
00:14:10,844 --> 00:14:23,890
And I'm like, right, but if we can't start at a solid baseline of what we all understand to be true, and how to name, like, when someone says this is offensive to me, you shouldn't argue with them.

141
00:14:24,091 --> 00:14:25,351
It's offensive to them.

142
00:14:25,371 --> 00:14:26,672
Accept that.

143
00:14:27,352 --> 00:14:53,558
apologize and and learn just like that's it sounds super basic but like I tell people this all the time racial equity work 90% of it is internalized you need to do your work you shouldn't be policing other people you need to call people in because that's the other thing that I think that happens a lot in in in the movement is that people

144
00:14:54,916 --> 00:14:57,520
want people to be all on the same level.

145
00:14:57,560 --> 00:14:58,621
And we're all on a journey.

146
00:14:58,661 --> 00:15:01,064
We're on the, I call it the road to enlightenment.

147
00:15:01,305 --> 00:15:03,147
And we're not all in the same place.

148
00:15:03,888 --> 00:15:05,130
And so we have to

149
00:15:08,310 --> 00:15:11,453
not accept racism, but just correct kindly.

150
00:15:11,934 --> 00:15:13,555
I always say correction is a kindness.

151
00:15:13,936 --> 00:15:23,846
And I'm telling you this, that you're saying something that is offensive to other people so that you don't offend somebody and that they also don't like lose their mind on you because you've said something offensive.

152
00:15:23,906 --> 00:15:29,011
Like I'm trying to save you from creating harm and having that guilt and harm to carry.

153
00:15:30,913 --> 00:15:38,936
So I do think that that's something that we absolutely, as a city, country, nation, state, everyone has to do this work.

154
00:15:39,737 --> 00:15:44,699
And if we're going to really, and it has to center the humanity of each other.

155
00:15:45,640 --> 00:15:48,721
I mean, because in the end, that's what racism is.

156
00:15:48,781 --> 00:15:52,843
It's a dehumanization of another person because they're different than you.

157
00:15:54,003 --> 00:16:04,308
And I think when you frame it like that, it kind of takes the energy out of like, you're calling me a racist, you're calling me a bigot, you're calling me, you know, whatever.

158
00:16:04,328 --> 00:16:08,150
And it's really about seeing, you know, everyone's human.

159
00:16:08,650 --> 00:16:08,870
Yeah.

